# 27_guides_scriptable_smoke — second row-bound model Scriptable
# end-to-end (s218 m1), modelled on 26_layers_scriptable_smoke.
#
# Validates the design banked in CANON's "Row-bound model Scriptables —
# collection-as-router with transient per-instance proxies" entry, now
# applied for the second time to the active document's guide surface.
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   guides         — collection. ONE registry entry. Set verbs (new,
#                    delete, color) and set queries (count, all_iids,
#                    color).
#   guides.<iid>   — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                    materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                    statement. Element verbs (toggle_locked /
#                    set_locked / x / y / angle) and element queries
#                    (locked / x / y / angle / type / iid).
#
# The shared `guides` prefix is load-bearing: the router splits a
# dotted token on the first `.`, looks the prefix up in the registry,
# and asks the matched object to resolve the suffix. Collection name
# and proxy prefix MUST be the same string.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every guide this script creates is bound to a script-local variable
# at creation time. Existing guides (whatever was in the doc when the
# script started) are NEVER touched: not toggled, not deleted, not
# moved. The teardown step at the bottom deletes only the guides we
# created, by bound iid.
#
# This is more permissive than the layers smoke (which uses
# "smoke_test_*" name prefixes to distinguish test guides — but guides
# have no name field, so the iid-binding pattern is the only way to
# track ours). Side effects on the doc's guide colour ARE reversible:
# we save the original at script start, do our colour round-trips, and
# restore it at teardown.
#
# ── Phases ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. BUILD UP  — capture the original guide colour, create three
#                  test guides, bind each iid to a variable (a / b / c).
#   2. VALIDATE  — exercise collection queries, doc-level colour, and
#                  per-instance verbs/queries on each bound variable.
#   3. TEAR DOWN — delete every test guide; restore the original
#                  guide colour; verify cleanup.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP ===
#[sub] Save the doc's current guide colour so teardown can restore it.
#[sub] The colour is doc-level state (one colour for all guides in the
#[sub] doc); we round-trip it in Phase 2 and put it back at the end.

get guides color
set orig_color to result

#[sub] Create three test guides. `guides new` returns the iid of the
#[sub] new guide; `set X to result` binds it. Default geometry is
#[sub] centred horizontal at canvas (w/2, h/2), angle 0 — the proxy
#[sub] verbs reshape each guide individually.

guides new
set a to result
assert guides.a type == "h"

guides new
set b to result
assert guides.b type == "h"

guides new
set c to result
assert guides.c type == "h"

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE ===
#[sub] Three test guides exist, bound to variables `a`, `b`, `c`.
#[sub] Exercise the per-instance surface through `guides.<var> <verb>`
#[sub] addressing.

#[sub] Element queries: locked (default false), iid (round-trip), type
#[sub] (h/v/a derived from angle). x and y are doc-canvas-dependent so
#[sub] we round-trip them via setters rather than asserting an exact
#[sub] default — different docs have different canvas sizes.

assert guides.a locked == false
assert guides.a angle == 0.0
get guides.a iid
get guides.a x
get guides.a y

#[sub] x / y / angle round-trip on `a`. Each verb is a direct write
#[sub] on the model (guides aren't undoable today — the inspector
#[sub] doesn't push commands for these either, so the Scriptable
#[sub] mirrors that posture exactly).

guides.a x 123.5
assert guides.a x == 123.5
guides.a y 456.5
assert guides.a y == 456.5
guides.a x 200.0
guides.a y 300.0
assert guides.a x == 200.0
assert guides.a y == 300.0

#[sub] angle round-trip. 0 → horizontal type, 90 → vertical type, any
#[sub] other → arbitrary (a). The `type` query reads the model's
#[sub] guide_is_horizontal / guide_is_vertical helpers, same axis-
#[sub] aligned tests the canvas snap/hit-test use.

assert guides.a type == "h"
guides.a angle 90.0
assert guides.a angle == 90.0
assert guides.a type == "v"
guides.a angle 45.0
assert guides.a angle == 45.0
assert guides.a type == "a"
guides.a angle 0.0
assert guides.a type == "h"

#[sub] toggle_locked / set_locked round-trip on `b`. The inspector's
#[sub] lock button mutates SceneNode::locked directly without a
#[sub] command push; the verb does the same.

assert guides.b locked == false
guides.b toggle_locked
assert guides.b locked == true
guides.b set_locked false
assert guides.b locked == false
guides.b set_locked true
assert guides.b locked == true
guides.b toggle_locked
assert guides.b locked == false

#[sub] Collection queries. count should be >= 3 (our three plus any
#[sub] pre-existing user guides). all_iids returns comma-separated
#[sub] iids in children order — we don't assert an exact count or
#[sub] order here because pre-existing user guides shift both; the
#[sub] presence of our bound iids in subsequent per-instance addressing
#[sub] is the real test that the collection's enumeration is wired.

get guides count
get guides all_iids

#[sub] Doc-level guide colour round-trip. `guides color "<hex>"`
#[sub] parses the hex string through color::from_hex and writes
#[sub] doc->guide_color_r/g/b. `get guides color` reads it back as a
#[sub] hex string. The default colour is cyan (#00bfff approx); our
#[sub] orig_color variable captured whatever was there at script start.
#[sub]
#[sub] Round-trip is bit-exact for pure-component hex values: the write
#[sub] goes through from_hex (3 doubles); the read goes through
#[sub] doc_guide_color_as_hex (3 lround-to-255s). For "#ff0000" the
#[sub] math is 255/255 = 1.0, lround(1.0*255) = 255 → "#ff0000".

guides color "#ff0000"
assert guides color == "#ff0000"
guides color "#00ff00"
assert guides color == "#00ff00"
guides color "#0000ff"
assert guides color == "#0000ff"

#[sub] Invalid hex is silently rejected — the inspector path uses
#[sub] ColorPickerPopover which emits valid hex by construction, so the
#[sub] from_hex parse failure here matches "user couldn't have produced
#[sub] this through the UI". Colour should stay at the last-good value.

guides color "not-a-hex"
assert guides color == "#0000ff"
guides color ""
assert guides color == "#0000ff"

#[sub] === Phase 3: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Restore the original guide colour from the variable saved at
#[sub] script start. Then delete every test guide using the bound
#[sub] variables. After deletion, addressing `guides.<var>` would
#[sub] dispatch to a dead iid — the router's proxy lookup fails because
#[sub] the iid is no longer in the model. We rely on the `delete`
#[sub] verb's own `ok` report rather than asserting post-delete state.

guides color orig_color
assert guides color == orig_color

guides delete a
guides delete b
guides delete c

#[sub] Registry sanity — list at end. `guides` should appear exactly
#[sub] once, alongside `layers` and whatever other registered entries
#[sub] exist. No `guides.<iid>` entries despite the dozens of transient
#[sub] proxies materialised across this run.

list

#[sub] Done. Build-up captured the original guide colour and created
#[sub] three test guides bound to variables. Validate exercised every
#[sub] element verb (toggle_locked / set_locked / x / y / angle) and
#[sub] every element query (locked / x / y / angle / type / iid), plus
#[sub] doc-level guide colour round-trips. Tear-down restored the
#[sub] original colour and deleted every test guide. The user's
#[sub] original guides (if any) and the doc's guide colour preference
#[sub] are unchanged.
